<h1>To John Blair</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<p style="text-indent: 0;"><span style="float: left;">To The President.</span><span style="float: right;">[Fort Loudoun, 24 April 1758]</span></p>  
<p style="text-indent: 0; clear: both;">Honble Sir,</p> 
<p style="clear: both;">Your letter of the 19th instant, intended to come by Colo. Stephen, was delivered me to-day, about noon, by Express. As there are several matters contained in it of an interesting nature, I chose to be aided in my determinations, by the advice of my Officers; and have enclosed, your Honor their, and my opinion on the several heads.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>I coud by no means think of executing (willingly) that discretionary power, with which you were pleased to invest me, of ordering out the Militia. It is an affair, Sir, of too important and delicate a nature, for me to have the management of; for much discontent will be the inevitable consequence of this Draught.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0140">[140]</span>
<p>Your Honor will no longer be at a loss for a Return, after you receive my letter by Jenkins; and, lest any accident may have happened to that, I herewith enclose another for the same month.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>When the Relief for our outposts in augusta, marches, Major Lewis, who commands on that Quarter, should be advised thereof, and he will order them to their stations.</p>
<p>That was a most extraordinary request of Colo. Mercer, concerning the exchange of Officers; and calculated, it should seem, rather to breed confusion, and to gratify his own vanity, than to benefit the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">other</span> Regiment.</p>
<p>There is not an Ensign <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">there</span>, that would not rather quit the Service, than accept of a company in the other Regiment; so much do they disapprove Colo. Mercers proposal; and I have neither <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">inclination</span> nor <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">power</span> to force their compliance.</p>
<p>Captn Rutherfords company was raised and posted on this quarter by Governor Dinwiddies express orders, and can be more useful here than any other men whatever, being all sons of the neighbouring farmers, men of property, young active, and entirely acquainted with the woods on these frontiers: Whereas, if they go to the southward, they will be utter strangers to the enemys haunts, and of no more use there than the militia of an adjacent County; while their places here must be supplied by Militia equally ignorant of <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">these</span> woods, as <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">they</span> will be of any <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">others</span>, besides giving them an useless march of 2,00 miles, and exposing the frontiers in the mean time. Another reason may be urged: their property all lies in this County: Interested motives induced them to enlist, and to be vigilant in defending <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">it</span>: and, I believe, they would <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">desert</span>, rather than go to the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">southward</span>.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>If your Honor will please to remember, it was one among the last questions I had an opportunity of asking, if I shoud send parties a recruiting? You replied, that, as the Assembly was so near meeting, you woud defer giving any directions on that head.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> and, as I had no money for that purpose, I hope it will not seem surprizing, that we have recruited but a few men since; and that I have been waiting for Orders to complete the Regiment. I shall now use my best endeavours, with what few officers can be spared from the Garrisons (which will be very few, indeed!) dispersed as we are.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0141">[141]</span>
<p>I shall also be under a necessity of sending down for money to carry on this Service; and should be glad that your Honor woud order it to be ready immediately, to prevent delay of the officer, who will set off to-morrow, or the next day after, at the farthest. I am &amp;c.</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">G:W.</p>
<div class="dateline-closer">Ft Loudoun, the 24th April, 1758.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Blairs letter of 19 April has not been found, but <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0104" class="document">GWs enclosed Council of War, 24 April</a>, gives further indication of what the letter contained. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0105" class="document">GW to Adam Stephen, 24 April</a>, and to <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0106" class="document">Thomas Waggener, 25 April</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0094" class="document">GW to Blair, 17 April</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>After reading a letter of 10 April from Col. Clement Read of Lunenburg County about many Robberies and Murders committed lately in Bedford and Hallifax counties, Blair and the council decided that both Capt. Peter Hogs and Capt. Robert Rutherfords companies of rangers should range on the So. Western Frontiers (11 April 1758, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ H. R. McIlwaine et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Executive Journals of the Council of Colonial Virginia&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Richmond, 192566. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Exec. Journals of Virginia Council</span></span>, 6:8687). GW repeated the argument he makes here against moving Rutherfords rangers made on 10 May in his letter to Blair of 410 May. He also had made a similar argument earlier for the initial appointment of Robert Rutherford of Frederick County rather than Peter Hog of Augusta County as ranger captain in Frederick County (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0001" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 5 Oct. 1757</a>). The president and council considered this letter from GW of 24 April at a meeting on 1 May, and on 2 May the councilors advised Blair to discharge the said Company [of Rutherfords rangers], but employ the Men notwithstanding, as Part of the Militia, in garrisoning some of the Forts (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ H. R. McIlwaine et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Executive Journals of the Council of Colonial Virginia&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Richmond, 192566. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Exec. Journals of Virginia Council</span></span>, 6:8889). Blair seems not to have done this, however (see for instance <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0181" class="document">GW to Robert Rutherford, 24 June 1758</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0103-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>GW and Blair must have talked of this when GW was in Williamsburg in March 1758. The assembly met on 30 Mar., and GW was back at Mount Vernon en route to Winchester by 1 April. For GWs movements in March 1758, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0073&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0073-fn-0006#GEWN-02-05-02-0073-fn-0006" class="document">GW to John Stanwix, 4 Mar., n.6</a>. For further information about the measures GW took to recruit men for the 1st Virginia Regiment, see particularly <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0120" class="document">GW to Blair, 410 May</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0120&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0120-fn-0013#GEWN-02-05-02-0120-fn-0013" class="document">note 13</a> of that document.</p>

</div>
